    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 1,
      "text": "Overview"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "IPCC is inter-process communication controller"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "IPCC uses signals for inter process communication. Signals are delivered as interrupts. IPC controller is a centralized block for managing IPC interrupts at SoC level. IPCC uses star topology and requires only one IRQ input wire per core per protocol. IPCC provides the functionality for multiple processors to communicate and synchronize"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "There are two instances of IPCC, one instantiated at the SAILSS level and the other at the SoC level. IPCC is used to implement the internal and external mailbox feature to share data between the cores"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "It replaces the mesh network of the IRQ lines between different subsystems with a centralized hardware block with routing logic (STAR topology). The IPCC provides the functionality for multiple processors to communicate and synchronize"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "The IPCC implements different networks called protocols . Each protocol could support up to 64 clients, but the actual number for specific platform may vary. The register set of each client is on 4 KB boundary"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 1,
      "text": "IPCC Protocols"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Below are the protocols uses in QAM8775"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": false,
      "items": [
        "MPROC protocol",
        "Compute0 protocol",
        "Compute1 protocol",
        "PCIEMSI protocol",
        "SAIL Mproc protocol"
      ]
    },
    {
